05442nam a22008175i 9780226693491DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019035336  a97802266934917 a10.7208/97802266934912doi  a(DE-B1597)549362  a(OCoLC)1151188880  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aPN690.C7bG35 2020 4aPN690.C7bG35 2020 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a809/.933582072231 aGalvez, Marisa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Subject of Crusade :bLyric, Romance, and Materials, 1150 to 1500 /cMarisa Galvez. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b14 color plates, 12 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tIntroduction. The Courtly Crusade Idiom -- tChapter One. The Unrepentant Crusader: The Figure of the Separated Heart -- tChapter Two. Idiomatic Movement and Separation in Middle High German and Occitan Crusade Departure Lyric -- tChapter Three. The Heart as Witness: Lyric and Romance -- tChapter. Four Lancelot as Unrepentant Crusader in the Perlesvaus -- tChapter Five. Three Ways of Describing a Crusader-Poet: Adjacency, Genre-Existence, and Performative Reconfigurations -- tChapter Six. The Feast of the Pheasant as Courtly Crusade Idiom -- tConclusion. Toward a More Complex View of Crusade -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the Middle Ages, religious crusaders took up arms, prayed, bade farewell to their families, and marched off to fight in holy wars. These Christian soldiers also created accounts of their lives in lyric poetry, putting words to the experience of personal sacrifice and the pious struggle associated with holy war. The crusaders affirmed their commitment to fighting to claim a distant land while revealing their feelings as they left behind their loved ones, homes, and earthly duties. Their poems and related visual works offer us insight into the crusaders’ lives and values at the boundaries of earthly and spiritual duties, body and soul, holy devotion and courtly love. In The Subject of Crusade, Marisa Galvez offers a nuanced view of holy war and crusade poetry, reading these lyric works within a wider conversation with religion and culture. Arguing for an interdisciplinary treatment of crusade lyric, she shows how such poems are crucial for understanding the crusades as a complex cultural and historical phenomenon. Placing them in conversation with chronicles, knightly handbooks, artworks, and confessional and pastoral texts, she identifies a particular “crusade idiom” that emerged out of the conflict between pious and earthly duties. Galvez fashions an expanded understanding of the creative works made by crusaders to reveal their experiences, desires, ideologies, and reasons for taking up the cross.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aCrusades in art. 0aCrusades in literature. 0aPoetry, MedievalxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aHoly Land.  aambivalence.  aconfession.  acrusade.  alyric.  amanuscripts.  amaterials.  apenance.  apiety.  apilgrimage.  apreaching.  aromance.  asacrifice.  atapestries.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:d